TopicTitle: Unplayably broken terrain in linux AMD

Articles.Content:
Hello,

I have installed KSP (64 bit) through steam on Linux Mint 17.3 64bit, and are using the AMD fglrx drivers. I am using the latest 1.1.3 version.

The terrain is UNPLAYABLY BROKEN, not rendering at all at close distances - as shown in the included screenshots.

It is a clean linux install, and the bug is reproducible on multiple computers, all using AMD's fglrx drivers. The problem occurs on both the 32bit and 64bit version of KSP.

The KSP.log file is as follows:

Hi Wilson wilson, have you tried -force-glcore yet?

-force-gfx-direct is the old Unity4 command, it still exists but has been superseded.

-force-glcore will force the Unity5 engine to redetect the versions of OpenGL on your system, and by appending a number you can force a specific version, -force-glcore33 will force OpenGL 3.3 for example.

Also, if you're using the fglrx driver from the repository please note that it is rather old, and you would be better off with the driver from the AMD website.

Thankyou for replying so fast.

I tried adding the launch option 

-force-glcore

instead (along with multiple opengl versions), but the game crashed on startup as if there was no launch option.

Then I tried both launch options at the same time - 

-force-gfx-direct -force-glcore

The terrain works fine, and the game is now playable. BUT, I now have some wierd shadow bugs - as shown here:

Yes, by AMDGPU I mean AMDGPU-Pro, which is Catalyst replacement. But its correct - AMDGPU is a new kernel-side open driver, which is shared between open user-side driver (Mesa) and closed user-side driver AMDGPU-Pro.
AMDGPU + Mesa//AMDGPU-Pro

Previously Catalyst had own kernel module (like nvidia) and open driver kernel driver was called "radeon" which is still active because new driver model is active only.
Basically this and more compact version.

AMDGPU-Pro is not Mesa replacement, God help.



And AMDGPU-Pro is different from Mesa ("all open" on the slides) and its Mesa which should be used for base testing, and not the AMDGPU-Pro.
